  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_1' aria-label=\" Lalita versus Vishwanath & Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('1','2025','2025_1_1643_1658','2025INSC173'); ><font size='4'> <strong>LALITA<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>VISHWANATH & ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 1 S.C.R. 1643</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 173</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010004932025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Matter pertains to the correctness of the order passed by the High Court acquitting the respondents for the offence punishable u/ss.306, 498A, and 34 IPC; and incase the first informant dies before stepping into the witness box, whether the contents of such FIR can be and read into the evidence. Headnotes&dagger; Penal Code, 1860 &ndash; ss.306, 498A, 34 &ndash; Abetment of suicide &ndash; FIR by the father that his daughter committed suicide as she was constantly harassed by the respondents-husband, in-laws and first wife of the husband &ndash; Respondents<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 30-01-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CRIMINAL APPEAL No. 1086/2017</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Dismissed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('1','2025','2025_1_1643_1658','2025INSC173','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('1','2025','2025_1_1643_1658','2025INSC173','H'); ><i class='fas f